  {
    "page": 5,
    "block_id": "p09_v_szz_automatic_identification_version_ranges_2022:block:005:031",
    "block_type": "text",
    "text": "inducing commit, some vulnerable versions would be considered\nas not vulnerable.\nTo detect the cherry-picked commits for a commit, we can search\nits commit id in the commit message because a sentence with the\nfollowing pattern is automatically generated in the commit mes-\nsage: “cherry picked from commit xxx”. However, some commits can\nbe copied to another branch without explicit information in the\ncommit message. For example, Figure 4 present two commits with\nthe same change from the project OpenSSL. The below commit in\nthe figure is copied from the above commit for an upgrade. We use\na hash-based duplicated change detection method to identify the\ncommits copied to other branches without explicit messages. We\nfirst hash the hunks of all commits in a project repository. Given a\ncommit, we search for the commits that contain all the hashes in it.\n",
    "bbox": [
      53.79800033569336,
      409.4942321777344,
      295.5453796386719,
      564.3512573242188
    ],
    "reading_order": 31,
    "column_guess": null,
    "confidence": "medium"
  },
  {
    "page": 5,
    "block_id": "p09_v_szz_automatic_identification_version_ranges_2022:block:005:032",
    "block_type": "text",
    "text": "Vulnerable version detection. In this step, we want to identify\nthe versions affected by a vulnerability based on a set of fixing com-\nmits and their corresponding inducing commits. In a Git workflow,\nproject maintainers usually assign a tag to a commit for a release\nversion, such as ‘‘n3.1’ in FFmpeg and ‘OpenSSL_1_0_0-stable’ in\nOpenSSL. Hence, our goal is to identify these commits with ver-\nsion tags that are affected by a vulnerability. The idea is intuitive,\ni.e., the vulnerability introduced by the inducing commits will be\ntransferred to the future commits until it gets fixed. Thus, the vul-\nnerable versions are between the inducing commits and the fixing\ncommits. We first identify the commits with version tags that are\nreachable to the inducing commits (denoted as Ci). A commit A is\nreachable to another commit B, indicating that A belongs to the\n",
    "bbox": [
      53.48400115966797,
      565.7542724609375,
      295.54833984375,
      709.6512451171875
    ],
    "reading_order": 32,
    "column_guess": null,
    "confidence": "medium"
  },
  {
    "page": 5,
    "block_id": "p09_v_szz_automatic_identification_version_ranges_2022:block:005:033",
    "block_type": "text",
    "text": "parents or the ancestor commits of B. We also identify the commits\nwith version tags that are reachable to the fixing commits (denoted\nas Cf ). Then, we can get the set of the vulnerable versions Cv, i.e.,\nthe set difference of Ci and Cf (i.e., Ci −Cf ).\nAs shown in Figure 3, the two commits in green color are not\nvulnerable because the one in the first branch is after a fixing\ncommit and the other one in the second branch is not reachable\nto the inducing commit. The vulnerable versions in the figure are\nmarked as brown. Finally, the output of this step is a set of version\ntags that are affected by a vulnerability, see an example in Figure 1.\n",
    "bbox": [
      317.6230163574219,
      284.6452331542969,
      559.5712280273438,
      395.8522644042969
    ],
    "reading_order": 33,
    "column_guess": null,
    "confidence": "medium"
  },
